description:
## Finding

secretx-tpm2 always converts errors to strings before boxing into `SecretError::Backend { source }`:

```rust
// tpm2 — always format!().into()
.map_err(|e| SecretError::Backend {
    backend: BACKEND,
    source: format!("failed to connect to TPM: {e}").into(),
})
```

The other hardware-backed siblings preserve the original typed error via `e.into()`:

```rust
// pkcs11 — preserves CkError
SecretError::Backend {
    backend: BACKEND,
    source: e.into(),   // e: CkError
}

// aws-kms — preserves service error type
SecretError::Backend {
    backend: BACKEND,
    source: svc.to_string().into(),
}
```

(AWS KMS also stringifies in `classify_kms_sdk_error`, but that is because the SDK error type is generic and cannot be boxed directly. The pkcs11 pattern is the gold standard.)

## Impact

Callers that downcast `source` to inspect the underlying error type (e.g. for retry logic beyond the Unavailable/Backend split, or for logging structured error codes) get `None` from `source.downcast_ref::<tss_esapi::Error>()` because the boxed value is a `String`, not the original TSS error.

This also affects error chain debugging: `anyhow::Error` and `tracing` show the causal chain from `#[source]`, but a boxed `String` has no cause chain — the TPM error code that would help an operator diagnose "TPM_RC_AUTH_FAIL vs TPM_RC_HANDLE" is flattened into an opaque message.

## Locations

- `/home/mark/PROJECT/crate-secretx/secretx-tpm2/src/lib.rs` — `map_tpm_error()` (line 215–250) and all inline `.map_err()` closures (~12 sites)
- `/home/mark/PROJECT/crate-secretx/secretx-pkcs11/src/lib.rs` — `classify_ck()` (line 75–104) — preserves typed error for comparison
